{"title_page": "Neil Ferreira", "text_new": "{{short description|Zimbabwean cricketer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{no footnotes|blp=|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name              = Neil Ferreira\n| image             = \n| caption           =\n| batting           = Left-hand bat\n| bowling           = Right-arm offbreak\n| columns           = 2\n| column1           = [[Test cricket|Tests]]\n| matches1          = 1\n| runs1             = 21\n| bat avg1          = 10.50\n| 100s/50s1         = 0/0\n| top score1        = 16\n| deliveries1       = -\n| wickets1          = -\n| bowl avg1         = -\n| fivefor1          = -\n| tenfor1           = -\n| best bowling1     = -\n| catches/stumpings1= 0/-\n| column2           = [[First-class cricket|First-class]]\n| matches2          = 40 \n| runs2             = 2515\n| bat avg2          = 34.93\n| 100s/50s2         = 9/8\n| top score2        = 220*\n| deliveries2       = -\n| wickets2          = -\n| bowl avg2         = -\n| fivefor2          = -\n| tenfor2           = -\n| best bowling2     = -\n| catches/stumpings2= 84/8\n| international     = true\n| country           = Zimbabwean\n| testdebutfor      =\n| testdebutagainst  =\n| testdebutdate     = 7 August\n| testdebutyear     = 2005\n| lasttestdate      = 7 August\n| lasttestfor       =\n| lasttestagainst   =\n| lasttestyear      = 2005\n| source            = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/55421.html ESPNcricinfo]\n| date              = 7 June\n| year              = 2012\n}}\n\n'''Neil Robert Ferreira''' (born 3 June 1979 in Salisbury - now [[Harare]]) is a [[Zimbabwe]]an [[cricket]]er.\n\nHaving also tried his hand at sports including tennis, squash, and hockey, he made his name as a left-handed opening batsman for the academy and for Manicaland. He is also a [[wicket keeper]]. His first Test involvement was in the August 2005 Test against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]].\n\nPrior to playing for his country Ferreira also played first-class cricket for Manicaland C.C scoring an impressive 501 runs in the 1999-2000 season and once again in the 2001-02 season taking out leading run scorer with 650 runs. On 8 August 2005 Ferreira received his Zimbabwean test cap being the 70th cricketer to represent Zimbabwe. Ferreira opened the batting for Zimbabwe's first innings but only managed 5 runs off 9 balls, Zimbabwe were then dismissed for just 59 and New Zealand captain Stephen Fleming enforced the follow on and once again Ferreira opened the batting and was dismissed for 16 runs off 90 balls, Zimbabwe were then all out for 99.\n\nFerreira has raised three sons two of which were playing B-Grade for Great Southern Grammar. Matthew Ferreira an all round right hand batsman and right arm leg spinner and Michael Ferreira a top order left hand batsman and a handy right arm medium pace.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}. The third of which Colin Ferreira attending Great Southern Grammar participating in extracurricular actives by playing 3 widely different instruments. \n\n==External links==\n* {{ESPNcricinfo|id=55421}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferreira, Neil}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Falcon College]]\n[[Category:CFX Academy cricketers]]\n[[Category:Manicaland cricketers]]\n[[Category:Matabeleland cricketers]]\n[[Category:Mashonaland cricketers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwe Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean cricketers]]\n\n\n{{Zimbabwe-cricketbio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Zimbabwean cricketer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{no footnotes|blp=|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name              = Neil Ferreira\n| image             = \n| caption           =\n| batting           = Left-hand bat\n| bowling           = Right-arm offbreak\n| columns           = 2\n| column1           = [[Test cricket|Tests]]\n| matches1          = 1\n| runs1             = 21\n| bat avg1          = 10